body: I don't think it's an issue. It's an internal file, you shouldn't include it directly.

> I don't think it's an issue. It's an internal file, you shouldn't include it directly.

That's a longer reply than adding `#pragma once`......

There's no way for us to tell easily if a file is internal or not.
When we found an usable function, by default we'll include the minimum file for it.
In this case it's non-trivial to trace upward and figure out which file should we include.
I'll add a comment to say the file is private, don't include it directly.
I agree that adding "#pragma once" should be done.
@snnn based on comments here, can you make the suggested update?
@xkszltl, have you tried the fix locally yet? Does it fully solve your problem?
In general we don't fix ort locally to avoid inconsistency with upstream.

snnn asked since we expect you to get other errors even if '#pragma once' was added.

That file is only included by 'onnxruntime_cxx_api.h' if you try to include it directly you'll get other compile errors since it'll try to define implementations for class members of classes that have not been defined.

> snnn asked since we expect you to get other errors even if '#pragma once' was added.
> 
> That file is only included by 'onnxruntime_cxx_api.h' if you try to include it directly you'll get other compile errors since it'll try to define implementations for class members of classes that have not been defined.

I see, I was able to just use cxx_api.
The problem I ran into is because I found a function in cxx_inline so I included it in addition to cxx_api and caused redef.
